	You can influence the DR/BDR election by changing the OSPF interface priority and the OSPF Router ID.&nbsp; The highest interface priority value wins during an election. Those&nbsp; values range from 0 to 255. The sequence works like this:


		During an election, the routers choose the router with the highest interface priority.

		If the interface priority ties, the election chooses the router with the highest OSPF RID.


	The other two settings mentioned in the answers, the reference bandwidth, and the OSPF process ID, have no impact on the DR/BDR election.

	&nbsp;

&nbsp;

	The two correct answers reference reasons why two routers will not become OSPF neighbors. They must be in the same OSPF area, and they must have identical OSPF Hello and Dead interval settings.

	For the incorrect answers, note that the routers are allowed to use different OSPF process ID settings (as configured on the router ospf process-id global command.) For the other incorrect answer, static routers have no impact on OSPF&#39;s logic.

